Sir Frederick Graham, thinking it unwise to leave such a record of some of the studies of a great man to the charge of a single manuscript, very kindly approved my suggestion to have the contents printed, and most liberally entrusted the volume to my hands for that purpose. The publication of it in the ordinary way would not (I wasinformed by a publisher) have been re- munerative: hence the means now adopted for its perpetuation.
